We make a couple of redundant arguments implicit, rename two misnamed theorems, and add two new ones.

---

I'm not sure if the theorems I renamed actually had the correct name; if they did, then [`Equiv.Set.sumCompl_symm_apply_of_mem`](https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/Logic/Equiv/Set.html#Equiv.Set.sumCompl_symm_apply_of_mem) and [`Equiv.Set.sumCompl_symm_apply_of_not_mem`](https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/Logic/Equiv/Set.html#Equiv.Set.sumCompl_symm_apply_of_not_mem) should be renamed instead to match.

Is `of_pos` (and `of_neg`) an established convention here? Can it be documented in the naming conventions?

There is some precedent in `if_pos` and `if_neg`. 

I'm open to other suggestions, just note that I'm trying to match these lemmas' names to `Equiv.Set.sumCompl_symm_apply` and `Equiv.Set.sumCompl_symm_apply_compl`.

Confusingly, `if_pos` and `if_neg` are in shape more like the (IMO correctly-named) `symm_apply_of_pos` and `symm_apply_of_neg` lemmas you have above. Perhaps worth a zulip poll to resolve the name bikeshedding, otherwise this looks good.
It looks like the current state of this PR is "needs a discussion and possibly a PR to the mathlib naming conventions"?
